solutions.content:
**Idea:**
We initialize position to 0,0 and direction to north.

**Example - going left:**
* if pos is [1,1], direction is [0,1] we want to go left - we have to add to pos [-1,0] (left in graph)
* if pos is [1,1], direction is [-1,0] we want to go left - we have to add to pos [0,-1] (down in graph)
* if pos is [1,1], direction is [0,-1] we want to go left - we have to add to pos [1,0] (right in graph)

That calculation brings us to the conclusion that for going left we change the direction [x,y] to [-y,x]
and for going right we change the direction [x,y] to [y,-x]

If position got back to original, or we changed original direction, the answer is True.

**Time Complexity:** O(n)
**Space Complexity:** O(1)

**C++:**
```
class Solution {
public:
    bool isRobotBounded(string instructions) {
        pair<int, int> pos = {0, 0}, dir = {0, 1};

        for (auto instruct : instructions) {
            if (instruct == 'L')
                dir = {-dir.second, dir.first};

            else if (instruct == 'R')
                dir = {dir.second, -dir.first};

            else
                pos = {pos.first + dir.first, pos.second + dir.second};
        }

        return ((pos.first == 0 && pos.second == 0) || (dir.first != 0 || dir.second != 1));
    }
};
```
