# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
This is a variation of the problem: [Minimum Time to Collect All Apples in a Tree](https://leetcode.com/problems/minimum-time-to-collect-all-apples-in-a-tree/description/)

Suppose, we have this input graph given to us:

![image.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/75a79632-81d9-49f6-b0bb-7d58bf460ed2_1673514772.6349287.png)

We first need to construct an adjacency list. We can create it using HashMaps in Java.

![image.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/3f8c04a9-d1a8-49cb-89b3-c6c135d5fac0_1673514909.0082629.png)

# Aprroach:
Our dfs function will do the following things:

- `Int[] dfs( int node, int parent ) :`

- For, Node 0 , Parent -1:

    - Initialize `nodeCounts[]` array that will keep the count of nodes having same labels.
    - We have an upper hand as labels will consist only of lower case English letters. This tells us that we can initialize the array with length = 26.
    - Our current node has label **‘a’** 
    So, `nodeCounts[‘a’-’a’]  = nodeCounts[0] = 1`;
    - Now, get `childCounts[]` for each `child` from `adjList[node]`.
    `childCounts[] = dfs(child, node)`
    - Update ``nodeCounts[]` for each `label` with the `childCounts[]`.

- Finally, update `ans[]` array, `ans[node] = nodeCounts[‘a’]`
- return `nodeCounts[]`;


# Simulation of left subtree from root:

We recursively go and visit the leaf node which is the left most subtree.

![image.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/ce271b89-3b26-419b-b018-04a603b6febe_1673515243.359908.png)

Then, we do as mentioned above and return to **node 1**.

Now, we do calculations in **node 1**.

![image.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/740f84d5-5d8e-4e28-a4b1-d142e322f74e_1673515328.6632729.png)

In the above figure you can see the childCounts returned from left subtree. Then, we have updated the nodeCounts array using it. We haven't shown the right subtree **node 5** in this calculation.

Finally, we calculate the `ans[1]`. You can see from the figure that we found it to be 1.

Then, we return the updated `nodeCounts[]` we got from the subtree.

Now, after returning at the root node:

![image.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/99156bf0-da69-4137-bfdd-7667aca25771_1673515844.6126533.png)


We do this calculation and update our `ans[]` array. You can see from the figure that `ans[0] = 1`. But it will be $$2$$ after we have traversed the right subtree.

**Be aware that we have only shown the calculations of the left subtrees in the example.**


After our final calculation of both subtrees:

![image.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/422b9471-e703-4e9c-858f-42188504b964_1673516013.8307922.png)

Our final ans array will be: `ans[] = {2, 1, 1, 1, 1, 1, 1}`

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(26*n) = O(n)$$
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: $$O(26*n) = O(n)$$
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
    Map<Integer, List<Integer>> adjList;
    int[] ans;
    String labels;
    public int[] countSubTrees(int n, int[][] edges, String labels) {
        adjList = new HashMap<>();
        ans = new int[n];
        this.labels = labels;
        for(int[] edge : edges){
            List<Integer> fromList = adjList.getOrDefault(edge[0], new ArrayList<>());
            fromList.add(edge[1]);
            adjList.put(edge[0], fromList);

            List<Integer> toList = adjList.getOrDefault(edge[1], new ArrayList<>());
            toList.add(edge[0]);
            adjList.put(edge[1], toList);
        }
        dfs(0, -1);
        return ans;
    }

    int[] dfs(int node, int parent){
        char ch = labels.charAt(node);
        int[] nodeCounts = new int[26];
        nodeCounts[ch - 'a'] = 1;

        if (!adjList.containsKey(node)){
            return nodeCounts;
        }

        for(Integer child : adjList.getOrDefault(node, new ArrayList<>())){
            if(child == parent){
                continue;
            }
            int[] childCounts = dfs(child, node);
            for (int i = 0; i < 26; i++) {
                nodeCounts[i] += childCounts[i];
            }
        }

        ans[node] = nodeCounts[ch - 'a'];

        return nodeCounts;
    }
}
```

