solutions.content:
Keys:
1) A tree, is also a connected, undirected graph that has no cycles; since the input edges are out of order and for each edge we don't konw which end of this edge is the parent, thus, it's better to treat this relationship as connected-neighbors instead of parent-child;
2) DFS: we know that 0 is always the root(start node in this undirected acyclic graph), thus during dfs, we just have to let the function to rule out the parent node from current node's neighbors and we know that there's no circle in this graph, therefore, this dfs works perfectly;
3) Counter: a node needs a counter of all the labels in its subtree(including itself), and this counter can be obatined by merging all its children's counters and adding the counter of its label by 1(divide and conquer, the reason for using dfs).

Thus, here's what this code does:
1) build map, for each edge [a, b], put a into b.neighbors and put b into a.neighbors; 
2) DFS, starts from 0, for each node, iterate through all its children(neighbors except parent), obtain and merge all the children's subtree counters(I use hashmap in this code), update the counter by increntment the counter of current node's label, put current node's labels' counter into the record map(where we store the result of this problem), then return the counter of current node;
3) transform the record map into the ans array, and return.

Time: O(n)
1) Initialization - O(n), since there are `n-1`edges;
2) DFS - O(n), visit each node once & each edge once;
3) Transform - O(n), because of n nodes.

Space: O(n)
1) 2 Maps & ans array - O(n), because of n nodes
2) Counter - O(26n) -> O(n), since labels are lower-case characters, the size of each counter would not be larger than 26. 

Also, using array with length of 26 as counter might be easier and faster.
```
class Node{
    public List<Integer> neighbors;
    public Node(){
        neighbors = new ArrayList<Integer>();
    }
}

class Solution {
    public int[] countSubTrees(int n, int[][] edges, String labels) {
        // 1) Initialize
        HashMap<Integer, Node> map = new HashMap<>();
        for(int[] edge : edges){
            Node node1 = getNode(map, edge[0]);
            Node node2 = getNode(map, edge[1]);
            node1.neighbors.add(edge[1]);
            node2.neighbors.add(edge[0]);
        }

        // 2) DFS
        HashMap<Integer, Integer> record = new HashMap<>();
        helper(map, record, 0, labels, -1);
        int[] ans = new int[n];
        for(Map.Entry<Integer, Integer> entry : record.entrySet())
            ans[entry.getKey()] = entry.getValue();
        return ans;
    }

    public HashMap<Character, Integer> helper(HashMap<Integer, Node> map, HashMap<Integer, Integer> record, int n, String labels, int parent){
        Node node = getNode(map, n);
        HashMap<Character, Integer> counter = new HashMap<>();
        counter.put(labels.charAt(n), 1);
        for(Integer child : node.neighbors){
            // Parent is one of the neighbors but should not be counted as part of subtree
            if(child == parent)
                continue;
            HashMap<Character, Integer> childCounter = helper(map, record, child, labels, n);
            for(Map.Entry<Character, Integer> entry : childCounter.entrySet()){
                // Merge child's counter
                Character key = entry.getKey();
                Integer val = entry.getValue();
                counter.put(key, counter.getOrDefault(key, 0) + val);
            }
        }
        record.put(n, counter.get(labels.charAt(n)));
        return counter;
    }


    public Node getNode(HashMap<Integer, Node> map, Integer n){
        if(map.containsKey(n))
            return map.get(n);
        Node node = new Node();
        map.put(n, node);
        return node;
    }
}
```

