# Intuition
I want to return upwards what characters I have seen somehow during dfs.

# Approach
Make adjacency list for faster access to connected nodes. Using int array found to store the cnt of every char seen. And finally res vector to store the result. I keep track of the parent node so I don't just return randomly upwards. For every child I make another newFound int array because if I use the same one the result will be wrong for some nodes.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
O(N) for making adj list and another O(N) for dfs (every node is visited only once). So in total O(N).

- Space complexity:
O(C*N), where C is some constant, so O(N)

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    vector<vector<int>> adj;
    void cnt(int cur, int parent, int found[], string &labels, vector<int> &res)
    {
        for (int child : adj[cur])
        {
            if (child != parent)
            {
                int newFound[26] = {0,};
                cnt(child, cur, newFound, labels, res);

                for (int i = 0; i < 26; ++i)
                {
                    found[i] += newFound[i];
                }
            }
        }

        ++found[labels[cur] - 'a'];
        res[cur] = found[labels[cur] - 'a'];
    }

    vector<int> countSubTrees(int n, vector<vector<int>>& edges, string labels) {
        adj.resize(n);
        for (const vector<int> &e : edges)
        {
            adj[e[0]].push_back(e[1]);
            adj[e[1]].push_back(e[0]);
        }

        int found[26] = {0, };
        vector<int> res(n);

        cnt(0, -1, found, labels, res);

        return res;
    }
};
```

