# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
Use DFS to visit every node starting with the root node. From each node return an `int[]` that contains the summed up count of all node letters of the current node and all its children. Look up the `int[]` map at each node to record the desired count in the final result `int[]`.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
1. Compute an adjacency list for all nodes using `int[][] edges`.
2. Intiate a DFS traversal from the root node (#0).
3. At each node, create a `int[]` map which will store the count of each lowercase letter contained in the subtree.
4. Update the `int[]` map to account for the current node's label.
5. Sum up the values of the `int[]` maps of each of the child nodes with the current node's map.
6. Record the count of the current node's label character in the `int[]` result structure. This count will have accounted for all the nodes in the subtree.
6. Return the current node's `int[]` map to the parent.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(n)$$
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: $$O(1)$$
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
  int[] ans;
  List<List<Integer>> adj = new ArrayList<>();

  private int[] dfs(int node, int parent, String labels) {
    int[] map = new int[26];
    map[labels.charAt(node) - 'a']++;

    for (int child : adj.get(node)) {
      if (child != parent) {
        int[] childMap = dfs(child, node, labels);

        for (int i=0; i<26; i++)
          map[i] += childMap[i];
      }
    }
    ans[node] = map[labels.charAt(node) - 'a'];
    return map;
  }

  public int[] countSubTrees(int n, int[][] edges, String labels) {
    ans = new int[n];
    for (int i=0; i<n; i++)
      adj.add(new ArrayList<>());

    for (int[] edge : edges) {
      adj.get(edge[0]).add(edge[1]);
      adj.get(edge[1]).add(edge[0]);
    }
    dfs(0, -1, labels);

    return ans;
  }
}
```

