# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
Use tradition dfs algorithm for we are interested in subtrees of any given node.

Keep a tab on the frequency of each label.

While at any given node store frequency of it's label uptill now before incrementing its frequency (because we want to include current value in our answer) then explore the subtrees whilst updating the frequency data structure.

Once you return from your traversal, simply find out the difference of total frequency of that label and the temporary frequency which you had stored earlier.

That's your answer!!!

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
Step 1: Create answer vector of size n.
Step 2: Create visitor vector of size n for dfs.
Step 3: Create adjacency list (Our tree).
Step 4: Create frequency vector to store the frequencies of each label.
Step 5: Populate adjacency list.
Step 6: Call DFS with starting at 0th node (It is given)
Step 6a: Set current node as visited.
Step 6b: Store frequency of current label uptill now.
Step 6c: Increment frequency of current character (for the current node).
Step 6d: Do a DFS and send everything as reference (Make sure to do this otherwise you will get TLE in some cases).
Step 6e: Calculate and store your answer.
Step 7: Return answer vector.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(N)
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->


- Space complexity: O(N)
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->


# Code
```
class Solution 
{
public:

    void dfs(int cNode, vector<vector<int>> &adj, vector<bool> &vis, vector<int> &freq, string &labels, vector<int> &ans)
    {
        vis[cNode] = true;
        int currFreq = freq[labels[cNode] - 'a']; 
        freq[labels[cNode] - 'a']++;

        for(int neighbor : adj[cNode])
        {
            if(!vis[neighbor])
                dfs(neighbor, adj, vis, freq, labels, ans);
        }

        ans[cNode] = freq[labels[cNode] - 'a'] - currFreq;
    }

    vector<int> countSubTrees(int n, vector<vector<int>>& edges, string labels)
    {
        vector<int> ans(n, 0);
        vector<bool> vis(n, false);
        vector<vector<int>> adj(n);
        vector<int> freq(26, 0);

        for(auto edge : edges)
        {
            adj[edge[0]].push_back(edge[1]);
            adj[edge[1]].push_back(edge[0]);
        }

        dfs(0, adj, vis, freq, labels, ans);

        return ans;
    }
};
