# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
Create an array count of size 26, where count[i] stores the number of nodes with label i in the subtree of the current node.
Create an array result of size n, where result[i] stores the number of nodes in the subtree of the ith node with the same label as node i.
Perform a depth-first search (DFS) traversal of the tree, starting at the root node (node 0).
For each node visited during the DFS, update the count array with the number of nodes with the same label as the current node in its subtree.
Once the DFS traversal is complete, copy the count array to the result array for the current node.
Repeat steps 4 and 5 for each child of the current node.
Return the result array.


# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
 O(n), where n is the number of nodes in the tree. We need to traverse all n nodes in the tree once
- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
 O(n), where n is the number of nodes in the tree.
We need to store the count and result arrays, which have a total size.
# Code
```
class Solution {
  public int[] countSubTrees(int n, int[][] edges, String labels) {
    int[] ans = new int[n];
    List<Integer>[] graph = new List[n];
    for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i)
      graph[i] = new ArrayList<>();
    for (int[] edge : edges) {
      final int u = edge[0];
      final int v = edge[1];
      graph[u].add(v);
      graph[v].add(u);
    }
    dfs(graph, 0, -1, labels, ans);
    return ans;
  }
  private int[] dfs(List<Integer>[] graph, int u, int parent, final String labels, int[] ans) {
    int[] count = new int[26]; 
    for (final int v : graph[u]) {
      if (v == parent)
        continue;
      int[] childCount = dfs(graph, v, u, labels, ans);
      for (int i = 0; i < 26; ++i)
        count[i] += childCount[i];
    }
    ans[u] = ++count[labels.charAt(u) - 'a'];
    return count;
  }
}
```

